# Executive Summary

Maximum Power Point Tracking (MPPT) controllers are today’s industry benchmark for solar charging systems, widely adopted because they are designed to extract maximum available power from solar panels.

Under ideal laboratory conditions, the DC-DC conversion stage of an MPPT can achieve efficiencies of up to **95–98%**.

However, in real-world outdoor use, overall system efficiency typically drops into the **70–85%** range.

This reduction is caused by:

* firmware overhead
* switching losses
* live-to-ground referencing
* inherent lag in continuously adjusting to changing irradiance

As a result, while MPPT sets the gold standard for solar control, its actual performance in the field is often well below the advertised peak values.

---

In contrast, the Reflex Solar Flow Controller is built on a fundamentally different principle.

It does not use:

* DC-DC converters
* pulse-width modulation (PWM)
* firmware-driven algorithms

All of which introduce internal consumption and switching losses.

Instead, Reflex relies on a repurposed voltage comparator operating through a threshold principle.

A small pair of non-rechargeable reference batteries provide the minimum threshold (live battery voltage), while the solar panel represents the maximum threshold.

Energy flows only when the solar panel voltage exceeds the reference battery voltage, ensuring that charging occurs naturally and efficiently.

This direct live-to-live comparison eliminates unnecessary circuitry, reduces system complexity, and removes the overhead that limits MPPT performance in the field.

By allowing the physical voltage differential to dictate the flow of energy, Reflex achieves higher real-world efficiency and stability with a fraction of the complexity of MPPT.

---

# Objective and Scope

The objective of this study was to evaluate whether the Reflex Solar Flow Controller achieves:

* higher charging efficiency
* superior real-world correlation with solar irradiance

than a conventional MPPT controller.

The systems were validated through tests on a standard **20W solar panel**.

---

# Experimental Setup

The experiments were designed to provide a direct side-by-side comparison between a conventional MPPT system and the Reflex Solar Flow Controller under identical solar conditions.

## Batteries

Two identical **18650 lithium-ion cells** were used as the load.

* nominal voltage: 3.7V
* maximum voltage: 4.2V

These cells served as the measurement baseline.

## Devices Under Test

### 1. MPPT Model

An existing Switching Battery KC5V product incorporating an MPPT IC was used.

The MPPT IC represented a conventional firmware-driven converter-based charging system.

### 2. Reflex Model

A modified version of the KC5V was built by removing:

* MPPT IC
* inductors
* PWM switching circuits

In their place, a repurposed voltage comparator was implemented.

This design embodied the Reflex principle:

* direct live-to-live comparison
* no DC-DC conversion
* no PWM
* no firmware overhead
* simplified architecture

## Solar Input

Two identical **20W solar panels (6V, 3.3A)** were used.

One panel connected to MPPT, the other to Reflex.

Panels were positioned side-by-side.

---

# Measurement Methodology

## Day 1

Manual data collection at 15-minute intervals.

Limitation:

Solar irradiance fluctuates within milliseconds, making coarse sampling insufficient.

## Day 2

Data logger captured **1-minute interval readings**.

This forms the primary comparative dataset.

## Day 3

Strong stable sunlight using Reflex alone.

Data captured at **15–20 second intervals**.

Over one hour:

* battery rose from 3.3V to 3.72V
* irradiance correlation above 0.95

This demonstrated microsecond-level response behavior.

